      <problem>
        <p>
          For any two cards, is it always possible to find a third card to complete a SET?  How many options do you have?  Justify your assertions.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <activity xml:id="activity-buildplane">
        <task>
          <p>
            Pick any three cards who do <em>not</em> form a set and arrange them in a corner of a <m>3\times 3</m> grid 
            like so: 
          </p>
          <image source="img/Partial_Set.png" />
        </task>
        <task>
          <p>
            Fill out this grid so that each row, column and diagonal forms a SET.
          </p>
        </task>
        <task>
          <p>
            For each pair of cards on this grid, is there a third card also on this grid which forms a SET?
          </p>
        </task>
      </activity>

      <problem>
        <p>
          For the grid you constructed in  <xref ref="activity-buildplane" />, how would you describe the position of
          the sets in relation to the grid?
